"{\"uid\": \"independent.co.uk-sport-olympics-alex-yee-triathlon-paris-2024-profile-b2581387.html\", \"text\": \"Notifications can be managed in browser preferences.  Please refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in  Swipe for next article  The 26-year-old triathlete is one of Britain's best hopes for gold in Paris  Removed from bookmarks  I would like to be emailed about offers, events and updates from The Independent. Read ourPrivacy notice  Alex Yeehopes he can inspire the next generation of triathletes with his performances in Paris as he takes over the mantle from the Brownlee brothers.  For the first time in 20 years, the name Brownlee will not feature in the British Olympic team, with Alistair now concentrating on other challenges and Jonny having missed out on selection.  Between them, the Yorkshire siblings won five Olympic medals, with Alistair the only triathlete to win two golds, in London and Rio, and Jonny having won individual bronze and silver, then gold in Tokyo three years ago as part of the team relay.  Anchoring that team was Yee, who was the individual silver medallist in Japan and goes into the Games as one of Britain's best hopes for gold.  Yee was born in 1998 and rose to prominence a British professional triathlete and distance runner. He won the silver medal in the Men's Triathlon and the gold medal in the Triathlon Mixed Relay at the Tokyo 2020Olympics.  Also a former British 10,000 metres champion on the track, Yee has built impressively on his 2021 success, winning double gold in the Commonwealth Games becoming the triathlon champion in both the men's and mixed team events. He is a double World Championship medalist over the World Triathlon Championship Series, with silver in 2022, and bronze in 2021 and is now one of Great Britain's brightest prospects to reach the podium in Paris.  Last August, Yee also completed the Olympic test event on the Games course and finished a surprising first against a strong field. After his victory he said: \\\"It gave me a god deal of confidence. I think things like that are definitely confidence boosters but also the fact that we were able to race on that course before is really powerful for me, and just being able to experience what we are hopefully going to experience. That's really exciting.\\\"  He has won both his races so far this season but there have also been disappointments, with Yee only finishing 30th in the World Series Finals last year to miss out on the global title. A lot of his races have come down to a sprint finish against New Zealand's Hayden Wilde, with Yee coming out on top on most occasions.  \\\"I'd certainly love that scenario but we will see what happens,\\\" he said, \\\"There is 60 other hungry guys on the start-line and everyone starts on a level playing field. I will race the best race I can do and execute the processes I have put in place and, hopefully, that puts me in a good place to be in a race with Hayden or whoever it will be.\\\"  Yee fondly remembers watching the Brownlees' success in London as a 14-year-old, and he told the PA news agency: \\\"They have created such a legacy for us, not only for the British male side of things but the whole of British triathlon in general.  \\\"We have been really lucky to have them. I guess the responsibility has now been passed on to us and we are going to do our best to represent our country andTeam GBthe best we can and hopefully make everyone proud.  \\\"From 2012 and being able to watch in my home town an Olympic Games, that's such a rare experience for most people so I have been extremely lucky in that sense. Then to be able to share a gold medal with Jonny in 2021 was really, really special. Hopefully I can be the inspiration like they have been for me for someone else down the line and carry on that legacy.\\\"  Join thought-provoking conversations, follow other Independent readers and see their replies  Please refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in\"}"